# Medusa Framework Guidelines

## Module Development
- Modules should be self-contained in [src/modules](mdc:src/modules)
- Export services, models, and workflows from module index
- Use dependency injection via Medusa's container system

## Service Pattern
```typescript
// Services extend MedusaService with models
export default class VendorService extends MedusaService({
  Vendor,
  VendorAdmin,
  Report,
}) {
  // Service methods follow CRUD patterns
  async createVendor(data: CreateVendorInput): Promise<Vendor> {
    return await this.create(Vendor, data)
  }
}
```

## Model Definition
- Models use MikroORM decorators
- Follow Medusa's entity patterns
- Include proper relationships and indexes

## API Routes Structure
- Store routes: [src/api/store](mdc:src/api/store) - Public-facing APIs
- Admin routes: [src/api/admin](mdc:src/api/admin) - Admin panel APIs  
- Vendor routes: [src/api/vendor](mdc:src/api/vendor) - Vendor-specific APIs

## Workflow Usage
- Use workflows for complex business logic
- Keep workflows focused and composable
- Handle errors gracefully in workflow steps

## Event Handling
- Use subscribers for event-driven logic
- Place in [src/subscribers](mdc:src/subscribers)
- Follow Medusa's event naming conventions

## Configuration
- Environment validation in [medusa-config.ts](mdc:medusa-config.ts)
- Module registration follows Medusa patterns
- Links configuration for custom relationships

## Testing
- Unit tests for services and utilities
- Integration tests for API endpoints
- Use Medusa's test utilities when available